[00:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hi, welcome to another video. So, Anthropic just released Claude Sonnet 4.6 and honestly, this one is complicated. On one hand, it feels nerfed compared to'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sonnet 4.5 in one-shot tasks. On the other hand, it absolutely dominates in agentic coding. And I mean dominates. It beat Opus 4.6 on my agent'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leaderboard. So, let me explain what\'s going on here. So, let\'s get right into it. Now, before I show you the numbers, let me give you a quick overview of what'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Anthropic claims. Sonnet 4.6 now has a 1 million token context window, which is currently in beta. The pricing stays the same as Sonnet 4.5'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at $3 per million input tokens and $15 per million output tokens. And it\'s now the default model on Claude for free and pro users.'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They also claim that in early Claude code testing, users preferred Sonnet 4.6 over Sonnet 4.5 about 70% of the time with users saying it reads context'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'better before modifying code. They even claim users preferred it over Opus 4.5 in 59% of comparisons, which is a pretty bold claim for a'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sonnet tier model. But here\'s the thing. When I ran it through King Bench, the one-shot benchmark I use to test models across general knowledge and coding tasks,'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the results were not what I expected. Sonnet 4.6 scored 59% overall. Sonnet 4.5 scored 62%. So,'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sonnet 4.6 actually went down by 3% compared to its predecessor. And it\'s not just a small dip. If you look at the leaderboard, Sonnet 4.5 was sitting at number eight.'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And Sonnet 4.6 dropped all the way to number 12. It\'s now behind models like Kimmy K 2.5 and Gemini 3.0 Flash Skyhawk. Now, let me break this down by category'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because the coding side actually tells a different story than the general knowledge side. On general knowledge, Sonnet 4.6 absolutely tanked. It went from 40% on Sonnet 4.5 down to'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '25% on Sonnet 4.6. That\'s a massive regression. On the math questions, question nine and question 10,'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sonnet 4.5 scored two out of 20 on both, which was already bad. But Sonnet 4.6 only scored five out of 20 on both. So, technically, it did slightly better'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on those two. But then, on the riddle question, question 11, Sonnet 4.5 got a perfect 20 out of 20. While Sonnet 4.6'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only scored five out of 20. That\'s a huge drop. On coding, both models scored 71%, which is basically the same. Sonnet 4.6 scored 15 out of 20 on the 3D'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'floor plan, 15 out of 20 on the SVG panda, 10 out of 20 on the Poké Ball, 15 out of 20 on the chessboard,'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '18 out of 20 on the 3D Minecraft, 16 out of 20 on the butterfly, 13 out of 20 on the Rust CLI tool, and 12 out of 20 on the blender script.'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, the coding performance is essentially identical to Sonnet 4.5. Now, here\'s what\'s really interesting. The cost actually went up.'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'On KingBench, Sonnet 4.5 cost about 43 cents to run the full benchmark, while Sonnet 4.6 cost about 80 cents. That\'s almost double.'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, you\'re paying more for a model that performs worse overall on one-shot tasks. And this is where my theory comes in. I think Sonnet 4.6 might actually be a retrained model that is smaller in size.'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Almost like they took what was supposed to be Sonnet 5 and shrunk it down. And because it regressed in some areas, they decided to call it Sonnet 4.6 instead.'

[04:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I am saying seems because I don\'t have any insider information, but the behavior is consistent with a smaller model that has been optimized for specific tasks.'

[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Think about it. The general knowledge dropped significantly. The coding stayed roughly the same. The cost went up, which could mean it\'s using more tokens'

[05:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to think through problems. Almost like it\'s compensating for having less raw knowledge by being more verbose. And it costs more per run, which you would not normally expect from'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a true upgrade. For context on the overall KingBench leaderboard, Opus 4.6 is sitting at number one with a perfect 100%'

[05:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tied with Gemini 3 Pro. GLM 5 is at number three with 79%. Opus 4.5 Max is at number four with 74%. GPT 5.2 x high is at number six with'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '65%. So, the Sonnet tier is really falling behind on one-shot tasks. Even Kimmy K 2.5, which is way cheaper, scored 64% and beat Sonnet 4.6.'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if you want to try Sonnet 4.6 for yourself in an agentic setup, it\'s already available on Kilocode, which is what I used for all my testing.'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Kilocl I is the command-line version that I\'ve been using a lot lately for agentic evaluations, and Sonnet 4.6 works great with it. Now, here\'s where the video takes a'

[06:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complete turn, because I also ran the full agentic coding benchmark on Sonnet 4.6, and the results are insane. Sonnet 4.6 paired with Kilocode'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scored 87.9 average on the KingBench leaderboard. That puts it at number one. Let me say that again. A Sonnet tier model is sitting at the'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'top of the entire agent leaderboard, beating everything. GLM 5 plus Kilocl I is at number two with 84.1. Opus 4.6 plus'

[07:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude code is at number three with 83.6. So, Sonnet 4.6 is beating Opus 4.6 in agentic coding. A Sonnet model'

[07:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'beating Opus, that\'s wild, and it\'s not just the numbers. I actually tested it on five real-world vibe coding projects to see how it handles complex multi-file applications'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from scratch. The first test was a go-based terminal calculator using bubble tea. Sonnet 4.6 built the entire thing. About 370 lines of go code'

[07:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with a proper grid layout, arrow key navigation, color-coded buttons, chained arithmetic, division by zero handling, comma-separated number formatting,'

[07:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and nine passing unit tests. It planned everything with a to-do list, executed it cleanly, and it just worked. Done in about 3 and 1/2 minutes.'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The second test was a React Native Expo movie tracker app with TMDB API integration. This one was impressive because it had to build a full design system from'

[08:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scratch. Red, blue, and yellow aesthetics with glassmorphism using blur views, a GitHub-style activity heat map calendar, TMDB movie search,'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'local storage for reviews and ratings, star ratings, status badges, the whole thing. It even set up proper TypeScript types, an API client, and async storage CRUD.'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All compiled with zero TypeScript errors. The third test was a Nuxt 3 Q&amp;A platform. This is where it gets really serious. Sonnet 4.6 built a full Stack'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Overflow-style app with server-sent events for real-time updates, incremental static regeneration, internationalization, drizzle, ORM, authentication,'

[09:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rate limiting, voting, comments, accepted answers, and markdown rendering. It even set up proper revision history for edits.'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The amount of code it wrote here was massive, and it organized everything cleanly across server API routes, database schemas, and front-end components. The fourth test was a SvelteKit Kanban'

[09:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'board with an offline mutation queue. So, it had to handle SQLite on the back end, IndexedDB in the browser for offline support, drag and drop with the Svelte'

[09:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'DND action library, and proper queue syncing when the connection comes back. It even set up Vitest unit tests and Playwright end-to-end test scaffolding.'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the fifth test was a cross-platform image cropping and annotation desktop app using Tauri. This is probably the most impressive one'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because it involved both Rust and TypeScript. On the Rust side, it built image processing commands, a system tray with export toggles, deterministic zip packaging with Blake3'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hashing, and project save and load. On the TypeScript front-end side, it built a full canvas renderer with zoom, pan, hit testing,'

[10:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an eight-handle resize tool, undo and redo with the command pattern, keyboard shortcuts, right-click context menus using native Tauri menus,'

[10:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a settings panel, and even a preview window. Both cargo check and the Vite build passed with zero errors. Now, compare all of that to Opus 4.6 with Claude code,'

[11:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which scored 83.6 on the agent leaderboard. Sonnet 4.6 plus Kilo beat it by over four points. And here\'s the kicker. Opus 4.6 costs $5 per million input'

[11:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tokens and $25 per million output tokens. Sonnet 4.6 costs $3 and $15 respectively.'

[11:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, you\'re getting better agentic performance for significantly less money. If you ask me for vibe coding, I prefer Sonnet 4.6 over Opus 4.6 and Code X.'

[11:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I know that sounds crazy given how the one-shot benchmarks look, but in practice, when you\'re building actual applications with an AI coding agent, Sonnet 4.6 just vibes better.'

[11:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It plans more carefully. It reads the existing code base before making changes. It breaks things down into logical steps,'

[12:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it follows through without getting lost in the middle of complex tasks. That\'s exactly what you want from an agentic coder. So, this brings me back to my theory. I think Anthropic deliberately optimized'

[12:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this model for agentic workflows at the expense of one-shot intelligence. It\'s like they took what might have been Sonnet 5, realized it was better at agentic tasks,'

[12:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but regressed on raw knowledge, and decided to release it as Sonnet 4.6 instead. And honestly, for the way most developers actually use these models today,'

[12:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is through coding agents like KiloCode, ClaudeCode, or Verdant, that might be the right trade-off. But I want to be balanced here. If you\'re using Claude through the chat'

[13:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interface for general questions, brainstorming, or quick one-shot coding tasks, Sonnet 4.6 is worse than Sonnet 4.5. There are some downsides.'

[13:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The general knowledge took a massive hit. It went from 40% to 25%, and it costs almost double to run on my benchmark. Those are real regressions that matter'

[13:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for certain use cases. But if you\'re vibe coding, building real projects, and using it through a coding agent, Sonnet 4.6 is the best Sonnet model I have ever tested.'

[13:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Number one on my agent leaderboard. Better than Opus 4.6. Better than everything else. And that\'s pretty amazing to be honest. Now, going forward, I\'m also going to be testing Sonnet 4.6 on Verdant,'

[13:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is great for giving a model multiple tasks at the same time, and just keeping tabs on it. So, I\'ll be throwing a bunch of parallel projects at Sonnet 4.6 through Verdant,'

[14:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and seeing how it handles that kind of multitask workflow. That video will be coming soon. So, it\'s a weird one. Nerfed in some places,'

[14:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'absolutely incredible in others. I think Anthropic made a deliberate choice here, and whether it works for you depends entirely on how you use the model. If you\'re an agentic coder, this is an'

[14:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'upgrade. If you\'re a casual user, it\'s a downgrade. So, there\'s that. Overall, it\'s pretty cool. Anyway, share your thoughts below and subscribe to the channel.'

